Raid basics, redundancy across disks.

Raid, the redundant array of independent disks, combines several physical disks into one logical device to gain redundancy, performance, or both. Linux supports software raid through the m-d-adm tool, built on the kernel's m-d subsystem, entirely independent of any hardware raid controller.

There are several raid levels, and the trade-offs are what matter. Raid zero, called striping, splits data across the disks for maximum speed, but offers no redundancy at all; lose one disk and everything is gone. Raid one, mirroring, keeps an identical copy on every disk, so you can lose all but one and still have your data; the cost is that capacity equals just the smallest disk. Raid five stripes data and adds one block of parity, tolerating a single disk failure with only one disk of overhead, but writes are slow and rebuilds on large modern disks are slow and risky. Raid six is like raid five but with two parity blocks, surviving two simultaneous failures, the safer choice when capacity matters. And raid ten combines mirroring and striping for fast, reliable storage at the price of halving your usable capacity.

Choosing a level comes down to your priorities. Raid one is the simplest redundancy, common for boot drives. Raid six is the safer parity choice for bulk capacity. Raid ten is the right default when performance and reliability both matter and you can spare the capacity. And raid five is increasingly discouraged for new builds with very large disks.

There is one warning you must never forget: raid is not a backup. It protects only against a disk physically failing. It does nothing against an accidental delete, ransomware, fire, theft, or filesystem corruption, because all of those faithfully replicate to every disk in the array. Always keep separate backups. You create and manage arrays with m-d-adm, giving it the create option, a raid level, the number of devices, and the disks; its configuration is saved so the array reassembles at boot, and you can watch its health through the kernel's m-d-stat file.
